SOS Biologiacal data visualisation: CRP

#load libraries: library(dplyr) library(tidyverse) library(ggplot2) library(“data.table”) library(stringr) library(“plyr”) library(ggpubr) library(DescTools) library(MESS)

First, we import the SOS_hormones_cleaned.csv file and remove participants who do not have CRP data at all 4 time points.

#import cleaned bioloigcal dataset:
setwd("~/Documents/8_Byrne_work/SOS_Bioloigical_data_cleaned")
SOS_CRP <- read.csv('SOS_CRP_cleaned.csv')
SOS_CRP$SampleID <- as.character(SOS_CRP$SampleID)

SOS_CRP <- SOS_CRP[4:8]
SOS_CRP <- (SOS_CRP %>% arrange(SampleID,Time))

#Remove participants who do not have all 3 timepoints:
SOS_CRP_T1 = SOS_CRP %>% filter(Time == "1")
SOS_CRP_T2 = SOS_CRP %>% filter(Time == "2")
SOS_CRP_T3 = SOS_CRP %>% filter(Time == "3")
SOS_CRP_T4 = SOS_CRP %>% filter(Time == "4")

Merge1 <-merge(SOS_CRP_T1, SOS_CRP_T2, by = "SampleID", all = FALSE, all.x = TRUE)
Merge2 <-merge(Merge1, SOS_CRP_T3, by = "SampleID", all = FALSE, all.x = TRUE)
SOS_CRP_reshaped <-merge(Merge2, SOS_CRP_T4, by = "SampleID", all = FALSE, all.x = TRUE)
column names ‘Time.x’, ‘CRP_Ave.x’, ‘CRP_log.x’, ‘CRP_nontran_win.x’, ‘Time.y’, ‘CRP_Ave.y’, ‘CRP_log.y’, ‘CRP_nontran_win.y’ are duplicated in the result
SOS_CRP_all_timepoints <- na.omit(SOS_CRP_reshaped)

#Merge to now include only the people who have all 4 timepoints:
SOS_CRP_final <- merge(SOS_CRP, SOS_CRP_all_timepoints, by = "SampleID", all = FALSE)
SOS_CRP_final <- SOS_CRP_final[1:5]
colnames(SOS_CRP_final) <- c("SampleID", "Time","CRP_Ave", "CRP_log", "CRP_nontran_win")
SOS_CRP_final <- (SOS_CRP_final %>% arrange(SampleID,Time))

#Clear variables no longer needed:
rm(SOS_CRP_T1, SOS_CRP_T2,SOS_CRP_T3,SOS_CRP_T4, Merge1, Merge2, SOS_CRP_reshaped, SOS_CRP_all_timepoints)

total <- unique(SOS_CRP$SampleID)
total_keep <- unique(SOS_CRP_final$SampleID)
perc_all_timepoints <- ((length(total_keep))/(length(total)))*100

# Identify where the maximum value is (T1-T4) and add as a variable to dataframe
PeakTime <- list()
PeakTime_id <- list()
Responders <- list()

for (i in unique(SOS_CRP_final$SampleID)) {
    idx <- which(SOS_CRP_final$SampleID==i, arr.ind=TRUE)
    #Get participants peak timepoint
    PeakTime[i] <- which.max(SOS_CRP_final$CRP_log[idx])
    #Get SampleID
    PeakTime_id[i] <- i
    #Using T1 > T2,T3,T4 as exclusion criteria, split group into "Responders" and "Not Responders"
      if (PeakTime[i] == "1"){ 
      Responders[i] <- "0"
      } else {
      Responders[i] <- "1"
      }
    }

PeakTime <- data.frame(PeakTime)
PeakTime <- t(PeakTime)
PeakTime <- data.frame(PeakTime)

PeakTime_id <- data.frame(PeakTime_id)
PeakTime_id <- t(PeakTime_id)
PeakTime_id <- data.frame(PeakTime_id)

Responders <- data.frame(Responders)
Responders <- t(Responders)
Responders <- data.frame(Responders)


Peak_time_all <- cbind(PeakTime, PeakTime_id, Responders)
#Clear variables no longer needed:
rm(PeakTime, PeakTime_id)

names(Peak_time_all)[1]<- "PeakTime"
names(Peak_time_all)[2]<- "SampleID"
names(Peak_time_all)[3]<- "Responders"

SOS_CRP_final <-merge(SOS_CRP_final, Peak_time_all, by = "SampleID", all = TRUE)
rm(Peak_time_all)
SOS_CRP_final$PeakTime <- as.factor(SOS_CRP_final$PeakTime)

We have split the data according to where the participant’s maximum CRP response occured; at time point 1, 2, 3 or 4. We can then plot the change over time, depending on the group variable “Peak Time”:

Overall <- ggline(SOS_CRP_final, "Time", "CRP_log", 
           group = "PeakTime",
           add = c("mean_sd", "jitter"),
           color = "PeakTime")

Some participants may be ‘non responders’, meaning they did not show a response to the task. If their peak response was at Timepoint 1, we have classified participants as ‘non responders’ (0). All other participants (who show peaks at Timepoints 2,3 or 4) are included as responders (1).

#Clear variables no longer needed:

We want to know whether responders (1) and ‘non-responders’ (0) showed a significantly different response at Timepoint 1:

#Do a t-test to compare whether non-responders(0) had a higher T1 than responders(1)
Time_point_1 <- SOS_CRP_final[1:7]
Time_point_1 = Time_point_1 %>% filter(Time == "1")

compare_means(CRP_log ~ Responders, data = Time_point_1,
              method = "t.test")

People show differing baseline levels of CRP responding. We can calculate their relative change from baseline (Timepoint 1) at Timepoints 2,3 and 4.

rm(i, idx)

#For each subject, normalise time points 2,3 and 4, to timepoint 1.
Normalised_values <- list()
Normalise_id <- list()

for (i in as.character(SOS_CRP_final$SampleID)) {
  idx <- which(SOS_CRP_final$SampleID==i, arr.ind=TRUE)
  SampleID_current <- i
  baseline <- SOS_CRP_final$CRP_log[idx[1]]
    for (t in 1:4){
    Normalised_values[idx[t]] <- (SOS_CRP_final$CRP_log[idx[t]] - baseline)
    Normalise_id[idx[t]] <- SampleID_current 
    }
}

#Reformat lists into data.frames     
Normalised_values <- data.frame(Normalised_values)
Normalised_values <- t(Normalised_values)
Normalised_values <- data.frame(Normalised_values)

Normalise_id <- data.frame(Normalise_id)
Normalise_id <- t(Normalise_id)
Normalise_id <- data.frame(Normalise_id)
#Merge two data.frames
Normalised_all <- cbind(Normalised_values, Normalise_id)

#Clear variables no longer needed:
rm(Normalised_values, Normalise_id)

#Rename columns for merge (SampleID, also helps for checking that the rows have matched appropriately)
names(Normalised_all)[1]<- "BL_Norm_CRP_log"
names(Normalised_all)[2]<- "SampleID"

#Merge with SOS_CRP_final and remove unecessary extra SampleID column:
SOS_CRP_final <- cbind(SOS_CRP_final, Normalised_all)
SOS_CRP_final <- SOS_CRP_final[1:8]

#Clear variables no longer needed:
rm(Normalised_all, baseline, i, idx, SampleID_current, t)

#Calculate the area under the curve for each responder: 
AUC_list <- list()
AUC_id <- list()

for (i in unique(SOS_CRP_final$SampleID)) {
    idx <- which(SOS_CRP_final$SampleID==i, arr.ind=TRUE)
    #Get participants AUC for T1-4:
    AUC_list[i] <- auc(
                SOS_CRP_final$Time[idx],
                SOS_CRP_final$BL_Norm_CRP_log[idx],
                from = min(1, na.rm = TRUE),
                to = max(4, na.rm = TRUE),
                type = c("spline"),
                absolutearea = FALSE,
                subdivisions = 100,
                )
    #Get SampleID
    AUC_id[i] <- i
}
#Reformat lists into data.frames     
AUC_list <- data.frame(AUC_list)
AUC_list <- t(AUC_list)
AUC_list <- data.frame(AUC_list)

AUC_id <- data.frame(AUC_id)
AUC_id <- t(AUC_id)
AUC_id <- data.frame(AUC_id)

#Merge two data.frames
AUC_all <- cbind(AUC_list, AUC_id)

#Clear variables no longer needed:
#rm(AUC_list, AUC_id)

#Rename columns for merge (SampleID, also helps for checking that the rows have matched appropriately)

names(AUC_all)[2]<- "SampleID"

#Merge with SOS_CRP_final and remove unecessary extra SampleID column:

We can see that the greatest change in CRP level occurs between T1 and T2. We are therefore interested to quantify the magnitude of this change per participant. If participant’s change is +ve (meaning an increase from T1 –> T2) = 1. If participant’s change is -ve (meaning a decrease from T1 –> T2) = 0:

T1T2_list <- list()
T1T2_id <- list()
T1T2_direction <- list()

for (i in as.character(SOS_CRP_final$SampleID)){
    idx <- which(SOS_CRP_final$SampleID==i, arr.ind=TRUE)
    T1T2_id[i] <-i
    T1T2_list[i] <-(SOS_CRP_final$CRP_log[idx[2]] - SOS_CRP_final$CRP_log[idx[1]])
     if (T1T2_list[i] > "0"){ 
      T1T2_direction[i] <- "1"
      } else {
      T1T2_direction[i] <- "0"
      }
    }

#Reformat lists into data.frames     
T1T2_list <- data.frame(T1T2_list)
T1T2_list <- t(T1T2_list)
T1T2_list <- data.frame(T1T2_list)

T1T2_id <- data.frame(T1T2_id)
T1T2_id <- t(T1T2_id)
T1T2_id <- data.frame(T1T2_id)

T1T2_direction <- data.frame(T1T2_direction)
T1T2_direction <- t(T1T2_direction)
T1T2_direction <- data.frame(T1T2_direction)

#Merge two data.frames
T1T2_all <- cbind(T1T2_list, T1T2_id, T1T2_direction)

#Clear variables no longer needed:
rm(T1T2_list, T1T2_id, T1T2_direction)

#Rename columns for merge (SampleID, also helps for checking that the rows have matched appropriately)
